-for-alleged-antitrust-violations-in-its-ad-tech-business-11674582792 ) :

The Justice Department is seeking the breakup of Google=E2=80=99s business =
brokering digital advertising across much of the internet, a major expansio=
n of the legal challenges the company faces to its business in the U.S. and=
 abroad. A lawsuit filed Tuesday, the Justice Department=E2=80=99s second a=
gainst the Alphabet Inc. following one filed in 2020, alleges that Google a=
buses its role as one of the largest brokers, suppliers and online auctione=
ers of ads placed on websites and mobile applications. The filing promises =
a protracted court battle with wide-ranging implications for the digital-ad=
vertising industry.

Filed in federal court in Virginia, the case alleges that Google abuses mon=
opoly power in the ad-tech industry, hurting web publishers and advertisers=
 that try to use competing products. Eight states, including California and=
 New York, joined the Justice Department=E2=80=99s lawsuit. The lawsuit ask=
s the court to unwind Google=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Canticompetitive acquisition=
s,=E2=80=9D such as its 2008 purchase of ad-serving company DoubleClick, an=
d calls for the divestiture of its ad exchange=E2=80=A6

Though largely invisible to internet users, the ad-tech tools controlled by=
 Google facilitate much of the buying and selling of digital ads that helps=
 fund online publishers. Google=E2=80=99s business includes a tool publishe=
rs can use to offer ad space, a product for advertisers to buy those slots =
and an exchange that automatically links bidders with webpages as they are =
being loaded for individual users=E2=80=A6

For years, Google has faced allegations from advertising- and media-industr=
y executives, lawmakers and regulators that its presence at multiple points=
 of the online ad-buying process harms publishers and gives it an unfair ad=
vantage over rivals. Google also operates the most popular search engine an=
d the largest online video-streaming site, YouTube, giving rise to allegati=
ons it has tilted the market in its own favor. Rivals say that Google=E2=80=
=99s power in digital advertising stems from a series of acquisitions Googl=
e used to build its ad-tech business, beginning with the company=E2=80=99s =
$3.1 billion purchase of DoubleClick. The FTC approved the merger in a cont=
roversial decision. Google went on to purchase a host of other startups inc=
luding the mobile-advertising company AdMob.

The full complaint is here ( https://www.justice.gov/opa/press-release/file=
/1563746/download ) ; it is quite long (149 double-spaced pages, all of whi=
ch I read, and which explains today=E2=80=99s late delivery!), but I though=
t it was well-written and very interesting, and worth your time. Here are t=
he key paragraphs from the introduction:

Competition in the ad tech space is broken, for reasons that were neither a=
ccidental nor inevitable. One industry behemoth, Google, has corrupted legi=
timate competition in the ad tech industry by engaging in a systematic camp=
aign to seize control of the wide swath of high-tech tools used by publishe=
rs, advertisers, and brokers, to facilitate digital advertising. Having ins=
erted itself into all aspects of the digital advertising marketplace, Googl=
e has used anticompetitive, exclusionary, and unlawful means to eliminate o=
r severely diminish any threat to its dominance over digital advertising te=
chnologies.

Google=E2=80=99s plan has been simple but effective: (1) neutralize or elim=
inate ad tech competitors, actual or potential, through a series of acquisi=
tions; and (2) wield its dominance across digital advertising markets to fo=
rce more publishers and advertisers to use its products while disrupting th=
eir ability to use competing products effectively. Whenever Google=E2=80=99=
s customers and competitors responded with innovation that threatened Googl=
e=E2=80=99s stranglehold over any one of these ad tech tools, Google=E2=80=
=99s anticompetitive response has been swift and effective. Each time a thr=
eat has emerged, Google has used its market power in one or more of these a=
d tech tools to quash the threat. The result: Google=E2=80=99s plan for dur=
able, industry-wide dominance has succeeded=E2=80=A6

By deploying opaque rules that benefit itself and harm rivals, Google has w=
ielded its power across the ad tech industry to dictate how digital adverti=
sing is sold, and the very terms on which its rivals can compete. Google ab=
uses its monopoly power to disadvantage website publishers and advertisers =
who dare to use competing ad tech products in a search for higher quality, =
or lower cost, matches. Google uses its dominion over digital advertising t=
echnology to funnel more transactions to its own ad tech products where it =
extracts inflated fees to line its own pockets at the expense of the advert=
isers and publishers it purportedly serves.

A lot of the stuff that Google is accused of doing is very shady. It certai=
nly has abused one specific aspect of its power to achieve and maintain the=
 position it is in. The biggest challenge for the Justice Department, thoug=
h, is that even if all of the allegations are true, that specific aspect =
=E2=80=94 the linchpin on which all of these alleged abuses rest =E2=80=94 =
isn=E2=80=99t a crime: it=E2=80=99s being an Aggregator, in this case of a =
specific type of advertiser.

Google=E2=80=99s Advertising Aggregation
--------------------------------

I=E2=80=99m going to make the case about Google=E2=80=99s Aggregation using=
 nothing but the Justice Department=E2=80=99s own complaints; that is the s=
ource of all quotes.

First, there is the prize: a publisher=E2=80=99s ad server.

As a general matter, publishers use only one publisher ad server to manage =
ad inventory in order to avoid discrepancies in tracking revenue or impress=
ions and to minimize the burden of having employees oversee two largely dup=
licative systems. Ultimately, there can only be one publisher ad server act=
ing as the final decision-maker as to which advertisement will fill each im=
pression=E2=80=A6

Google=E2=80=99s ownership of the leading publisher ad server, DFP, allowed=
 it to set the rules that governed how most publisher inventory in the mark=
et is sold. Google internally referred to publisher ad servers as the =E2=
=80=9Cad revenue operating system for publishers=E2=80=9D because they deci=
de who is offered a chance to buy publisher inventory and on what terms. No=
t content to operate in a free and competitive market, Google altered its p=
ublisher ad server rules to force more transactions=E2=80=94and more high-v=
alue transactions=E2=80=94through its ad exchange and advertiser platforms.=
 The changes did not allow Google=E2=80=99s ad exchange rivals to compete i=
n the same way or on the same terms, largely leaving them with the leftover=
 scraps of inventory that Google=E2=80=99s advertisers did not want, even a=
t artificially discounted prices.

That internal Google analogy to an =E2=80=9Coperating system=E2=80=9D is he=
lpful, as it highlights why control of the ad server is the most valuable p=
iece of the ad tech stack. And, as the complaint notes, Google got a big ju=
mp in owning the ad server space by acquiring DoubleClick in 2007:

The DoubleClick acquisition was a pivotal moment for Google=E2=80=99s displ=
ay advertising technology business and its strategy to dominate the ad tech=
 stack. The deal provided Google with direct access to website publishers (=
and their inventory) on DoubleClick=E2=80=99s publisher ad server and, for =
the first time, a significant presence on both the advertiser and publisher=
 sides of the ad tech stack. Google feared that if a rival acquired DoubleC=
lick, Google would not control all the tools that link Google=E2=80=99s adv=
ertisers with publisher inventory; in short, a rival could =E2=80=9Cdisinte=
rmediate=E2=80=9D Google. Disintermediation risked allowing another company=
 to control how and where publishers sell impressions to advertisers, somet=
hing Google would not tolerate because it would limit Google=E2=80=99s abil=
ity to generate monopoly profits. Setting the stage for what was to come, t=
he DoubleClick acquisition provided Google the unilateral power to implemen=
t a series of anticompetitive restraints, using its dominance on both the p=
ublisher and advertiser sides of the market to inhibit competition across t=
he entire ad tech stack.

Stratechery wasn=E2=80=99t around in 2007, but for what it=E2=80=99s worth,=
 I did not think at the time =E2=80=94 and absolutely do not think now =E2=
=80=94 that it should have been approved. By 2007 Google already had the ke=
y factor in place that would allow it to increase DoubleClick for Publisher=
s from 60% share to over 90% share: Google AdWords (now called Google Ads).

The seeds for Google=E2=80=99s eventual march toward a monopoly in ad tech =
were sown in the early 2000s, when it capitalized on its well-known search =
engine to start a profitable search advertising business. In 2000, Google l=
aunched Google Ads (then called AdWords2), a tool that allowed businesses t=
o buy advertisements that could be seen by Google search users right alongs=
ide Google=E2=80=99s popular search engine results. Businesses quickly lear=
ned the power of this instantaneous, highly-targeted advertising technique,=
 and they flocked to Google Ads as a result.

By the early 2000s, Google realized that these same advertisers would buy d=
igital advertisements on third-party websites as well. So Google stepped in=
 to profit (as a middleman) on digital advertising transactions having noth=
ing to do with Google or its search engine by creating an advertiser ad tec=
h tool for Google Ads=E2=80=99 customers that wanted to buy ad space on thi=
rd-party websites.

These two paragraphs are written in a rather menacing tone, as they must be=
: this is the linchpin I was referring to. Where, though, is the crime? The=
 DOJ itself notes that businesses flocked to AdWords of their own volition,=
 and Google responding to demand by expanding the places where AdWords coul=
d be placed is a good thing as well. Indeed, it is precisely the fact that =
it was such a good thing that Google acquired the power it has.

Google Ads=E2=80=99 unique and sizeable advertiser demand is what makes Goo=
gle=E2=80=99s ad exchange unavoidable for most website publishers. Google A=
ds=E2=80=99 demand is unique both in its volume and diversity of advertiser=
s (now with more than two million) and in its ability to attract advertiser=
s at scale who cannot effectively use any other digital display advertising=
 tool to purchase ads on the open web. Even for Google Ads=E2=80=99 adverti=
sers who can use alternative buying tools, many of them are pushed into Goo=
gle Ads in order to buy other forms of critical advertising inventory that =
Google makes available effectively only through its buying tools, such as p=
ortions of YouTube, Gmail, and Search ad inventory. Together, these charact=
eristics mean that Google Ads has a significant scale advantage by controll=
ing a unique demand group (that spends about $11.5 billion on display inven=
tory each year).

There is not, to be clear, anything locking a business into Google Ads broa=
dly; there are no exclusivity contracts or technical limitations on using m=
ultiple ad networks. Yes, you have to use Google Ads for a good amount of a=
d inventory on Google , but that is Google=E2=80=99s prerogative to define =
the means by which you buy advertising on its own properties; you can use w=
hatever you want for other properties. Of course it is more convenient to j=
ust do everything in Google: after all, you are already using Google Ads fo=
r ads on Google properties, so it is certainly easier to use Google Ads for=
 the rest of the web as well, and that is exactly what a lot of businesses =
=E2=80=94 particularly small and medium-sized ones =E2=80=94 do. And that r=
ight there is the foundation of Google=E2=80=99s power.

A 2014 Google experiment found that more than half of the impressions that =
publishers offered on its ad exchange would go unsold without the critical =
Google Ads=E2=80=99 demand. If the Google Ads=E2=80=99 demand was removed f=
rom the ad exchange, Google=E2=80=99s publishers would experience a 65% dro=
p in revenue because no advertisers outside of Google Ads were interested i=
n buying the unique impressions available or able to do so in light of the =
auction restrictions described below. Google congratulated itself on having=
 effectively locked out meaningful competition. At one Google strategy meet=
ing, Google executives applauded the fact the =E2=80=9Cunique Google Displa=
y Ad demand=E2=80=9D allowed it to justify =E2=80=9Cwhy we can charge 20%=
=E2=80=9D fees for open auction transactions won on AdX, even on transactio=
ns that did not use Google Ads=E2=80=99 buying tools.

AdX is Google=E2=80=99s ad exchange, and it is the only place to get Google=
 Ads. In other words, all of those advertisers who only use Google Ads are =
only available on AdX, and there are so many of them that no publisher can =
go without them. However, to get the best price from those ads =E2=80=94 wh=
ich is done through real-time bidding, which perfectly matches an advertise=
r with an impression =E2=80=94=C2=A0publishers had to use AdX via DoubleCli=
ck for Publishers. Google made it worth it for the publishers:

First, Google configured Google Ads to bid on Google=E2=80=99s AdX ad excha=
nge in a way that actually increased the price of advertising, to the benef=
it of publishers and the detriment of Google=E2=80=99s own advertiser custo=
mers. As one Google employee observed, Google Ads was effectively sending a=
 =E2=80=9C$3bn yearly check [to publishers] by overcharging our advertisers=
 to ensure we=E2=80=99re strong on the pub[lisher] side.=E2=80=9D In the sh=
ort-term, this conduct locked publishers into Google=E2=80=99s publisher ad=
 server by providing them a steady stream of intentionally-inflated prices =
for certain inventory, at the cost of Google=E2=80=99s own advertiser custo=
mers. But in the long run, Google=E2=80=99s actions harmed publishers as we=
ll by driving out rival publisher ad servers and limiting competition in th=
e publisher ad server market. In effect, Google was robbing from Peter (the=
 advertisers) to pay Paul (the publishers), all the while collecting a heft=
y transaction fee for its own privileged position in the middle. This condu=
ct turned the entire purpose of the digital advertising industry on its hea=
d. Rather than helping to fund website publishing, Google was siphoning off=
 advertising dollars for itself through the imposition of supra-competitive=
 fees on its platforms. A rival publisher ad server could not compete with =
Google=E2=80=99s inflated ad prices, especially without access to Google=E2=
=80=99s captive advertiser demand from Google Ads.

The way that Google shifted money from advertisers to publishers was by sub=
mitting two bids for ad slots from Google Ads (while other ad networks subm=
itted one bid); given that the price was set by the 2nd-place bid, this sys=
tematically increased the winning price for an ad, to the tune of that afor=
ementioned $3 billion/year. In other words, publishers who used DoubleClick=
 For Publishers not only got superior access to Google Ads, Google ensured =
they got paid more, further locking them in.

Notice, though, who is getting harmed here: it=E2=80=99s the individual adv=
ertisers who are paying more for the ad slots they are filling. Again, thou=
gh, those individual advertisers are not locked in. Indeed, if all of the G=
oogle Ads publishers left Google tomorrow Google=E2=80=99s entire hold on t=
his market would evaporate. But they won=E2=80=99t: Google is just too conv=
enient, and most of these advertisers are fairly unsophisticated and number=
 in the millions. The analogy here should be obvious: it is to the people w=
ho use Google Search. Yes, competition is a click away; the problem for peo=
ple frustrated by Google Search is that no one wants to click away.

In short, Google has Aggregated the long tail of advertisers, and that long=
 tail is so large that no publisher can do without them; Google has then le=
vered access to those advertisers into control of the =E2=80=9Coperating sy=
stem=E2=80=9D of advertising, and with that control systemically favored it=
self. But again, that control is rooted in the individual choice of adverti=
sers. Is that a crime?

No Duty to Deal
---------------

Of course Google doesn=E2=80=99t think so; the most important part of its r=
esponse to the DOJ ( https://storage.googleapis.com/gweb-uniblog-publish-pr=
od/documents/Setting_the_record_straight_about_our_advertising_technology_b=
usiness_vfhkfk1.pdf ) was the very last paragraph:

We don=E2=80=99t have a duty to bid on rival auctions. American antitrust l=
aw does not require companies to give business to rivals, but that is exact=
ly what DOJ is trying to force Google to do. DOJ=E2=80=99s complaint allege=
s that Google should bid on rival exchanges on behalf of Google Ads custome=
rs the same way it bids on Google=E2=80=99s own ad exchange. This claim mis=
ses the point that we=E2=80=99ve built our advertising technologies to inte=
roperate with 80 competing platforms for publishers and even more for adver=
tisers. Many publishers and advertisers who use our services also use rival=
 platforms.

This is the =E2=80=9Cno duty to deal=E2=80=9D argument I have discussed in =
the past, particularly in the context of the App Store ( https://stratecher=
y.com/2021/app-store-arguments/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6=
InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdG=
