case here is Verizon v. Trinko ( https://tile.loc.gov/storage-services/serv=
ice/ll/usrep/usrep540/usrep540398/usrep540398.pdf ) :

Firms may acquire monopoly power by establishing an infrastructure that ren=
ders them uniquely suited to serve their customers. Compelling such firms t=
o share the source of their advantage is in some tension with the underlyin=
g purpose of antitrust law, since it may lessen the incentive for the monop=
olist, the rival, or both to invest in those economically beneficial facili=
ties. Enforced sharing also requires antitrust courts to act as central pla=
nners, identifying the proper price, quantity, and other terms of dealing =
=E2=80=94 a role for which they are ill suited. Moreover, compelling negoti=
ation between competitors may facilitate the supreme evil of antitrust: col=
lusion. Thus, as a general matter, the Sherman Act =E2=80=9Cdoes not restri=
ct the long recognized right of [a] trader or manufacturer engaged in an en=
tirely private business, freely to exercise his own independent discretion =
as to parties with whom he will deal.=E2=80=9D

Verizon v. Trinko is the Aggregators ultimate defense: if a company acquire=
s demand, whether that be users or advertisers, it has no duty to give acce=
ss to that demand. And, by extension, as long as this precedent exists, it =
is going to be very difficult for regulators to win a case against any Aggr=
egator, including this one.

That=E2=80=99s not to say I don=E2=80=99t support this case: I actually do =
think that Google is abusive in the ad space, and if regulators are going t=
o pursue a potentially-doomed antitrust case this is the 2nd most important=
 one I think they can pursue (number one is of course the App Store). Some =
of Google=E2=80=99s actions are so egregious that the DOJ might be able to =
win; alternatively the case could make its way to the Supreme Court, which =
is the only way Trinko will ever be changed.

